            <div class="span6">
                <h2>Escrow usage</h2>

                <div class="accordion" id="faq2">
                    <div class="accordion-group">
                        <div class="accordion-heading">
                            <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#faq2" href="#collapse6">
                                <span class="sign"></span> What happens if I lose my escrow password?
                            </a>
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-heading -->

                        <div id="collapse6" class="accordion-body collapse">
                            <div class="accordion-inner">
                                Your escrow password cannot be recovered. If you lose it, you will have to close the transaction and release the funds to the other side. If both parties lose their passwords, any funds held in escrow will be lost.

                            </div><!-- /.accordion-inner -->
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-body -->
                    </div><!-- /.accordion-group -->

                    <div class="accordion-group">
                        <div class="accordion-heading">
                            <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#faq2" href="#collapse5">
                                <span class="sign"></span> What if something happens to your website, how can I get my coins?
                            </a>
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-heading -->

                        <div id="collapse5" class="accordion-body collapse">
                            <div class="accordion-inner">
                                When viewing an open transaction, both parties can save the webpage and all javascript code to disk by using (File -> Save in most browsers).<br /><br /> This saved webpage can then be used (even offline!) to assemble the multipart keys. You can also save the raw keys under the "Advanced" tab and use them with other open source implementations like <a href="http://www.bitescrow.org">bitescrow.org</a> or the <a href="https://github.com/casascius/Bitcoin-Address-Utility">Bitcoin Address Utility</a> <br /><br />As long as you save each transaction page to your harddrive, you will still be able to complete your transaction even if our site goes down.</div><!-- /.accordion-inner -->
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-body -->
                    </div><!-- /.accordion-group -->

                    <div class="accordion-group">
                        <div class="accordion-heading">
                            <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#faq2" href="#collapse8">
                                <span class="sign"></span> Is your website really an escrow?
                            </a>
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-heading -->

                        <div id="collapse8" class="accordion-body collapse">
                            <div class="accordion-inner">
                                Not in traditional sense, since we do not hold users' funds. A
better way to understand it is the bitcoins are held in the blockchain
locked up in three private keys. 
                            </div><!-- /.accordion-inner -->
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-body -->
                    </div><!-- /.accordion-group -->


                    <div class="accordion-group">
                        <div class="accordion-heading">
                            <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#faq2" href="#collapse7">
                                <span class="sign"></span> How do I withdraw coins from escrow?
                            </a>
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-heading -->

                        <div id="collapse7" class="accordion-body collapse">
                            <div class="accordion-inner">
                                The same way you would spend from a paper wallet.
                                <br /><br />
                                Collecting funds from escrow requires importing the Bitcoin Private Key which will be presented to you in Wallet Import Format (long string starting with a 5).<br /><br /> All of the following clients support importing private keys, please see their websites for instructions: Coinbase, Electrum,
MulitBit, Blockchain.info, Armory, Bitcoin Qt, Mycelium, and more.


                            </div><!-- /.accordion-inner -->
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-body -->
                    </div><!-- /.accordion-group -->

                    <div class="accordion-group">
                        <div class="accordion-heading">
                            <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#faq2" href="#collapseA">
                                <span class="sign"></span> I have a dispute, how does arbitration work?
                            </a>
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-heading -->

                        <div id="collapseA" class="accordion-body collapse">
                            <div class="accordion-inner">
                                Email us at <a href="mailto:support@anark.it">support@anark.it</a> and tell us what happened. Include as much detail as possible along with 
a copy of all communication (email with headers is preferred). We will then contact the other party for their response.<br /><br />
                                
                                After considering both sides, we will send the key to the
prevailing party, allowing them to unlock the bitcoins with their transaction password.</div><!-- /.accordion-inner -->
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-body -->
                    </div><!-- /.accordion-group -->
                    

                    <div class="accordion-group">
                        <div class="accordion-heading">
                            <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#faq2" href="#collapseE">
                                <span class="sign"></span> What is the "Session Code" and do I have to use it?
                            </a>
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-heading -->

                        <div id="collapseE" class="accordion-body collapse">
                            <div class="accordion-inner">
                                 The session code is actually an MD5 hash of the buyer's public key. By sending it to the seller via email, you are ensuring that we cannot swap your key for our key (man in the middle attack) and decrypt your session.
                                <br /><br />
                                The seller can check the emailed code matches the code shown in his web browser and feel confident that only the buyer can read his multi-part key.
                                <br /><br />
                                Even if you ignore it, your coins are still safe. But if you want 100% security, we recommend verifying the session code through email with the other party.
                            </div><!-- /.accordion-inner -->
                        </div><!-- /.accordion-body -->
                    </div><!-- /.accordion-group -->
                    

                </div><!-- /.accordion -->

